  <article>
  <!-- IP Rating Deep Dive -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="ip-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">IP Ratings Explained</div>
      <h2 id="ip-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        IP65, IP66 & IP69K: Choosing the Right Washdown Rating
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          The Ingress Protection (IP) rating system (IEC 60529) uses two digits to describe protection level. The first digit rates solid particle protection (6 = dust-tight). The second digit rates water protection. Food conveyors typically start at IP65 and go up to IP69K depending on the severity of the cleaning protocol.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-ink">Choosing the wrong IP rating is the most common and most expensive mistake in food conveyor specification.</strong> Under-specifying causes premature motor failures, bearing corrosion, and electrical faults. Over-specifying wastes budget that could go toward additional conveyors or automation. The right choice depends entirely on your sanitation protocol.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">IP65: Low-Pressure Water Protection</h3>
        <p>
          IP65 protects against low-pressure water jets from any direction (6.3 mm nozzle, 12.5 liters per minute at 3 meters). This rating handles splash zones, occasional wipe-down cleaning, and environments where the conveyor gets wet but does not face direct hose-down cleaning.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-ink">Use IP65 for:</strong> dry food packaging areas with periodic cleaning, beverage secondary packaging, bakery environments without direct washdown, and enclosed product-handling areas where only incidental splashing occurs.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">IP66: High-Pressure Water Protection</h3>
        <p>
          IP66 protects against high-pressure water jets from any direction (12.5 mm nozzle, 100 liters per minute at 3 meters). This rating handles standard food plant washdown where sanitation crews use pressure washers and spray wands during shift changes or end-of-day cleaning.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-ink">Use IP66 for:</strong> standard food processing washdown environments, produce handling, canning lines, and facilities where daily hose-down cleaning is part of the sanitation SOP. IP66 is the most commonly specified rating for food plant conveyors.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">IP69K: High-Pressure, High-Temperature Protection</h3>
        <p>
          IP69K (originally defined under DIN 40050 Part 9, now included in IEC 60529) protects against close-range high-pressure, high-temperature water jets: 80 C (176 F) water at 80-100 bar (1160-1450 PSI) from a distance of 100-150 mm, with the nozzle angled at 0, 30, 60, and 90 degrees to the enclosure. <!-- VERIFY: Exact IP69K test parameters per current IEC 60529 -->
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-ink">Use IP69K for:</strong> meat and poultry processing, dairy plants, seafood handling, and any facility running CIP (Clean-in-Place) cycles, high-pressure foam-and-rinse sanitation, or steam cleaning. USDA-inspected meat and poultry plants typically require IP69K on all motors and drives in the processing area.
        </p>
        <p>
          Dorner's AquaPruf series and Nercon's sanitary platforms offer IP69K-rated motor and drive configurations. IP69K components use stainless steel housings with special shaft seals and potted electrical connections. These components cost 3-5 times more than standard TEFC motors.
        </p>
      </div>

