  <!-- CIP / COP Cleaning -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="cip-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Cleaning Methods</div>
      <h2 id="cip-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        CIP and COP Cleaning for Food Conveyors
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Food plants use two primary cleaning approaches for conveyor systems: CIP (Clean-in-Place) and COP (Clean-out-of-Place). The cleaning method affects conveyor design, component selection, and total cost of ownership. Most food plants use a combination of both methods on different parts of the same conveyor system.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">CIP (Clean-in-Place)</h3>
        <p>
          CIP cleaning uses automated spray systems to circulate cleaning solution, rinse water, and sanitizer across conveyor surfaces without disassembly. Spray nozzles mount along the conveyor frame and target all product-contact surfaces. A typical CIP cycle runs: pre-rinse, alkaline wash, intermediate rinse, acid wash, final rinse, and sanitizer application.
        </p>
        <p>
          CIP-capable conveyors require specific design features:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Self-draining frame design:</strong> All surfaces slope toward drain points with no horizontal ledges or pockets that trap liquid.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Smooth, crevice-free welds:</strong> All welds ground flush to eliminate bacterial harborage points. No skip welds or spot welds on product-contact surfaces.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Sealed penetrations:</strong> Every bolt hole, bearing mount, and wire entry uses food-grade gaskets or silicone seals to prevent cleaning solution from entering cavities.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">IP69K components:</strong> All motors, drives, sensors, and enclosures withstand the temperature and pressure of CIP cleaning chemistry.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">No dead legs:</strong> No tubing or frame cavities where cleaning solution can pool without drainage.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">COP (Clean-out-of-Place)</h3>
        <p>
          COP cleaning requires removing components from the conveyor and cleaning them separately. The most common COP components are belts, rollers, and guards. Sanitation crews remove these parts and wash them in a COP tank or automated parts washer, then reinstall them after drying and inspection.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conveyors designed for COP cleaning feature:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Tool-free belt removal:</strong> Quick-release tensioners allow the belt to be removed without wrenches or keys. Dorner's AquaPruf tip-up tail design is a leading example.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Modular plastic belts:</strong> Individual belt links snap apart for tank cleaning. Acetal or polypropylene links resist cleaning chemicals and handle repeated disassembly cycles.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Hinged guards and covers:</strong> Guards swing open or lift off without tools for full frame access.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Quick-disconnect rollers:</strong> Rollers pop out of the frame for tank cleaning or replacement without removing the conveyor from the line.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Combined CIP/COP Approach</h3>
        <p>
          Many food plants combine CIP and COP. The conveyor frame and drive components clean via CIP spray systems during the sanitation cycle. The belt removes for COP tank cleaning, where it soaks in sanitizer solution, gets scrubbed, rinsed, and inspected before reinstallation. This combination provides the most thorough sanitation while keeping line downtime manageable.
        </p>
        <p>
          Nercon's sanitary conveyor platforms support this combined approach with quick-release belts on CIP-capable stainless frames. mk North America's modular designs also allow rapid belt change-outs during COP cycles.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sanitary Design Principles -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="design-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Sanitary Design</div>
      <h2 id="design-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Sanitary Design Principles for Food Conveyors
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Sanitary design goes beyond material selection. The geometry of every surface, joint, and cavity determines whether the conveyor can be cleaned effectively. USDA, 3-A, and BISSC standards all reference the same core design principles, even though each standard applies them differently.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Surface Finish Requirements</h3>
        <p>
          3-A Sanitary Standards specify maximum surface roughness of 32 microinch (0.8 micrometer) Ra for product-contact surfaces. Non-contact surfaces should be smooth enough to prevent soil accumulation. Electropolishing provides a smoother, more corrosion-resistant surface than mechanical polishing because it removes the surface layer of disturbed metal left by grinding operations. <!-- VERIFY: Current 3-A Ra requirement for conveyor surfaces specifically -->
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Corner Radii and Crevice Elimination</h3>
        <p>
          All internal corners on product-contact surfaces require minimum radii to prevent product accumulation and bacterial growth. 3-A standards specify a minimum 1/4-inch (6 mm) radius on internal corners. Larger radii are preferred. Square corners trap product and resist cleaning -- bacteria colonies establish in these dead zones and contaminate subsequent production runs.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sanitary conveyor manufacturers eliminate crevices by using continuous welds (no skip welds), avoiding threaded fasteners on product-contact surfaces, and using formed one-piece components instead of assembled multi-piece brackets.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Frame Design: Open vs. Enclosed</h3>
        <p>
          Sanitary food conveyors use open-frame construction that exposes all surfaces for inspection and cleaning. Hollow tubes and closed box sections trap moisture, cleaning chemicals, and bacteria inside cavities that cannot be accessed. Open-profile frames (like mk North America's extruded stainless profiles) or solid round-tube frames with continuous welds and no internal cavities are the standard sanitary approach.
        </p>
        <p>
          The frame must also allow cleaning access underneath the conveyor. Conveyors mounted on cantilever supports or open legs allow sanitation crews to clean the floor and underside without blind spots. Conveyors bolted to solid pads or enclosed bases create harborage zones under the equipment.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Self-Draining Surfaces</h3>
        <p>
          All frame surfaces must slope toward drain points. Standing water creates bacterial growth environments and dilutes sanitizer concentration. Self-draining design is especially critical on conveyor side rails, supports, and the underside of the belt return path.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Bearings, Seals, and Lubrication</h3>
        <p>
          Bearings in sanitary conveyors use sealed housings that prevent cleaning water from entering the bearing cavity and prevent lubricant from leaking onto the product. Food-grade lubricants (NSF H1 registered) are required for any bearing in a food contact zone. Sealed stainless steel bearing housings resist corrosion from cleaning chemicals.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some sanitary conveyors use self-lubricating polymer bearings that eliminate lubricant contamination risk entirely. These bearings cost more and wear faster than steel bearings but eliminate the need for lubricant management in food contact zones.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Belt Materials for Sanitary Applications -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="belts-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Sanitary Belt Materials</div>
      <h2 id="belts-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Belt Materials for Washdown Environments
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Belt material selection for sanitary conveyors balances four factors: FDA compliance, chemical resistance to cleaning agents, cleanability (surface texture and porosity), and detection capability (metal-detectable or X-ray detectable materials). The belt is the primary food-contact surface and the most frequently cleaned component on the conveyor.
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4 mt-8">
          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[700px]">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Material</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Temp Range</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Cleaning Method</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Best For</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">TPU (Polyurethane)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-22 to 176 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">CIP and COP</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">General food, bakery, snacks</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Silicone</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 500 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">COP</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Bakery dough, sticky products</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Modular plastic</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 250 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">COP (snap-apart)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Meat, poultry, seafood</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">SS Wire Mesh</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-100 to 1800 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">CIP</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Ovens, freezers, fryers</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Metal-detectable PU</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-22 to 176 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">CIP and COP</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Lines with metal detectors</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Temperature ranges are typical manufacturer specifications. Actual limits vary by manufacturer, belt construction, and chemical exposure. <!-- VERIFY: Temperature limits for each belt type --></p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Metal-Detectable Belting</h3>
        <p>
          Metal-detectable belt materials contain additives that allow inline metal detectors to identify belt fragments if the belt wears or breaks. Standard colors are blue (for visual detection against most food products) or white. Food safety programs like SQF, BRC, and FSSC 22000 increasingly require metal-detectable belting on lines with inline metal detection equipment. The cost premium over standard TPU belting is moderate.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Belt Color Standards</h3>
        <p>
          White and blue are the standard belt colors for food conveyors. White provides the best visual contrast for most contaminants. Blue is visible against nearly all food products and makes foreign-body detection easier during visual inspection. Some food plants use different colors for different product zones (e.g., red for raw meat, blue for cooked product) to prevent cross-contamination through belt mix-ups during COP cleaning.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- USDA and 3-A Acceptance -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="acceptance-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Regulatory Acceptance</div>
      <h2 id="acceptance-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        USDA and 3-A Acceptance for Washdown Conveyors
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          USDA acceptance and 3-A authorization are separate processes with different requirements, different governing bodies, and different scopes of application. Understanding which applies to your facility prevents over-specifying (wasting budget) or under-specifying (failing audit).
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">USDA Acceptance Process</h3>
        <p>
          Equipment manufacturers submit detailed engineering drawings and material specifications to the USDA's Equipment Design Review Program. USDA engineers review the design against their sanitary design criteria. Accepted equipment receives a letter of acceptance that references the specific model, configuration, and material specification reviewed. The letter does not transfer to modified configurations -- any change to frame dimensions, belt material, or motor position requires a new review submission.
        </p>
        <p>
          USDA acceptance is required for equipment in meat, poultry, and egg products processing under federal inspection. Dairy equipment falls under different USDA programs. Conveyor models from Dorner (AquaPruf) and Nercon carry current USDA acceptance letters. <!-- VERIFY: Current USDA acceptance status for these specific models -->
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">3-A Sanitary Standards Authorization</h3>
        <p>
          3-A authorization requires third-party verification that equipment meets the applicable 3-A standard. An authorized 3-A evaluator inspects the equipment against published criteria for material composition, surface finish, cleanability, drainability, and design geometry. Equipment meeting all criteria earns the right to display the 3-A symbol.
        </p>
        <p>
          3-A standards apply primarily to dairy processing equipment. However, many food safety audit schemes (SQF, BRC, FSSC 22000) reference 3-A design principles as best practice for all food-contact equipment. Meeting 3-A criteria provides a defensible standard of sanitary design during audits, even for non-dairy applications.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">When Acceptance Is Required vs. Optional</h3>
        <p>
          The following table clarifies when USDA and 3-A acceptance are mandatory versus recommended.
        </p>
      </div>

