        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the difference between IP65, IP66, and IP69K?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p><strong class="text-ink">IP65</strong> handles low-pressure water jets -- suitable for splash zones and light wipe-down cleaning. <strong class="text-ink">IP66</strong> handles high-pressure water jets from any direction -- suitable for standard food plant washdown. <strong class="text-ink">IP69K</strong> handles high-pressure, high-temperature water (176 F / 80 C at 1450 PSI) -- required for CIP cleaning, steam sanitation, and USDA-inspected meat/poultry plants.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is CIP cleaning on a food conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p><strong class="text-ink">CIP (Clean-in-Place)</strong> uses automated spray systems to clean the conveyor without disassembly. Spray nozzles mounted along the conveyor circulate cleaning solution, rinse water, and sanitizer across all product-contact surfaces. CIP-capable conveyors require self-draining frames, smooth crevice-free welds, sealed penetrations, and IP69K-rated components.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Do I need USDA acceptance for my food conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>USDA acceptance is required for equipment in <strong class="text-ink">federally inspected meat, poultry, and egg processing plants</strong> where the equipment contacts food or operates in the processing zone. Conveyors handling sealed packages in secondary packaging areas, and facilities not under federal USDA inspection, typically do not require USDA acceptance.</p>
            <p>Even when not legally required, USDA-accepted equipment demonstrates sanitary design compliance during SQF, BRC, and FSSC 22000 audits.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What surface finish do sanitary conveyors require?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>3-A Sanitary Standards specify <strong class="text-ink">32 microinch (0.8 micrometer) Ra</strong> maximum surface roughness for product-contact surfaces. Electropolishing produces a smoother, more corrosion-resistant finish than mechanical polishing. Non-contact surfaces should be smooth enough to prevent soil accumulation and facilitate cleaning.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
